    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-11-03T23:20:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-11-03T23:20:00-05:00" n="282"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <head>282. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d282fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1967–69, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 6 <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIC1">CHICOM</gloss>. Limited Official Use; Priority.
                        Repeated to Taipei, Moscow, Tokyo, Wellington, and Hong Kong. Further
                        reporting on the General Assembly debates on Chinese representation is in
                        the following telegrams from <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>: 3977
                        (November 5), 4005 (November 6), 4027 (November 7), 4070 (November 8), and
                        4121 (November 11). (All ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-11-04T04:20:00+00:00">November 4, 1969,
                        0420Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3957. Subject: <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> Debate Opens in
                    Plenary.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> debate began late morning Nov 3 (fol
                        expressions condolences on deaths Tanzanian Perm Rep <persName
                            corresp="#p_DABC1">Danieli</persName> and Malaysian Perm Rep <persName
                            corresp="#p_IDMY1">Ismail</persName>) with statements by Cambodia,
                        China, Japan, Afghanistan, New Zealand, and Algeria. Cambodia and Japan,
                        respectively, introduced “Albanian” and Important Question reses.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>New Zealand (<persName corresp="#p_SJV1">Scott</persName>) reiterated
                            <gloss target="#t_PRIMIN1">PriMin</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HK1">Holyoake</persName> general debate statement that
                            <gloss target="#t_CHIC1">ChiCom</gloss>s should be in <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>, and that time had come for new approach to
                        find sensible and just solution to problem. However, Albanian <gloss
                            target="#t_RES1">res</gloss> by expelling <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                            >GRC</gloss> wld be “clearly unjust” and “totally unacceptable” to
                            <gloss target="#t_GNZ1">GNZ</gloss>. He urged adoption <gloss
                            target="#t_IQ1">IQ</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_RES1">res</gloss> since issue was “in every sense” of
                        far-reaching consequences.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>At beginning <gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> statement, usual
                        supporters of Peking walked out. However, junior <gloss target="#t_AMB1"
                            >Amb</gloss> remained in <gloss target="#t_SOV1">Sov</gloss> chair.
                        Moreover, <gloss target="#t_EE1">EE</gloss> diplomat told <gloss
                            target="#t_DELO1">DelOff</gloss> Sovs do not plan speak on <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>. These inactions, including omission of
                        ref to Peking in general debate speech, are first open reflections in <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> of Sino-<gloss target="#t_SOV1">Sov</gloss>
                        conflict.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Debate continues tomorrow (Nov 4) with US statement scheduled late
                            AM.<note n="2" xml:id="d282fn2">The statement of <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                >U.S.</gloss> Representative J. Irving Whalley is printed in the
                            Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, December 1, 1969,
                            pp. 476–479.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_YCW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Yost</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
